<subSubSection id="C34065587A3FFFAFFCB5052C3107B1B2" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3FFFAFFCB5052C3107B1B2" blockId="17.[828,1437,1028,2075]" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFCB5052C3035B312" bold="true" box="[828,1028,1028,1051]" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">
Description. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFC45052C3035B312" bold="true" box="[972,1028,1028,1051]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Body</emphasis>
</emphasis>
length 
<quantity id="4CA29B367A3FFFAFFBDD052C3096B312" box="[1108,1191,1028,1051]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" unit="mm" value="1.7">1.7 mm</quantity>
, maximum body width 1.0 mm. Head and labrum black; uniformly yellowish; elytra uniformly yellowish; legs yellowish. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFAAF056C3153B352" bold="true" box="[1318,1378,1092,1115]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Head</emphasis>
with strong mesh-like microsculpture on interstices; punctation sparse, each puncture bearing pointed seta. Eyes separated by 2.7× the width of one eye in dorsal view. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFAA4058C31ADB3B2" bold="true" box="[1325,1436,1188,1211]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Pronotum</emphasis>
with sparse setiferous punctation similar to that on head; interstices with strong mesh-like microsculpture. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFAD105CC31ADB3F2" bold="true" box="[1368,1436,1252,1275]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Elytra</emphasis>
with 10 striae sharply impressed except anteromedially (widely around scutellar shield) where neither striae nor serial punctures are visible; intervals weakly convex at midlength and near apex; interval punctation sparse, setiferous; interstices without microsculpture. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFB7104AC3153B292" bold="true" box="[1272,1378,1412,1435]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13612A567A3FFFAFFAE404AC3779B2B2" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[151,182,1467,1486]" captionTargetBox="[178,1432,202,1437]" captionTargetId="figure-13@18.[151,1436,186,1450]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 9. Male genitalia of Thysanarthria species, holotypes. A–E – T. saurahana sp. nov. (A–C – whole aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view; D–E – detail of median lobe and parameres in dorsal and ventral view). F–J – T. siamensis Hebauer, 2001 (F–H – whole aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view; I–J – details of parameres and median lobe in dorsal and ventral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4488942" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4488942/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Figs 9</figureCitation>
A–E) 
<quantity id="4CA29B367A3FFFAFFC03048C37EAB2B2" box="[906,987,1444,1467]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
long. Phallobase slightly widened at base of parameres, c. as wide as parameres combined, slightly narrowed towards basal fifth and abruptly widened at base; arcuate in lateral view. Paramere narrowly elongate, subequal in width throughout, apex abruptly narrowing into a short mesoapical ʻtooth’. Median lobe much shorter than parameres, with strongly sclerotized shorter part arcuate apically, and membranous apical part rounded apically; gonopore large, triangular, situated subapically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34065587A3FFFAFFCB507EC3066B0D2" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3FFFAFFCB507EC3066B0D2" blockId="17.[828,1437,1028,2075]" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFCB507EC3008B1D2" bold="true" box="[828,1081,1732,1755]" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3FFFAFFBCB07EC3167B1D2" authorityName="Fikáček &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2019" box="[1090,1366,1732,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Thysanarthria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saurahana">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFBCB07EC3167B1D2" box="[1090,1366,1732,1755]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Thysanarthria saurahana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species in Himalaya with strong mesh-like microsculpture on the pronotum (in contrast to pronotum without microsculpture in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3FFFAFFC72060C30B5B032" authorityName="Knisch" authorityYear="1924" box="[1019,1156,1828,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Chaetarthria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="championi">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFC72060C30B5B032" box="[1019,1156,1828,1851]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">T. championi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3FFFAFFB3C060C3107B032" authorityName="Hebauer" authorityYear="2001" box="[1205,1334,1828,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Thysanarthria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siamensis">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFB3C060C3107B032" box="[1205,1334,1828,1851]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">T. siamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and with weak granulate microsculpture in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3FFFAFFB17066C311EB052" authorityName="Hebauer" authorityYear="2001" box="[1182,1327,1860,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Thysanarthria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madurensis">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFB17066C311EB052" box="[1182,1327,1860,1883]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">T. madurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It can be distinguished from all these species as well as from all other 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3FFFAFFCB506AC37E4B092" authorityName="Fikáček &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2019" box="[828,981,1924,1947]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Thysanarthria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFCB506AC37E4B092" box="[828,981,1924,1947]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Thysanarthria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of parameres and the unique morphology of the median lobe which is not similar to any other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34065587A3FFFACFCB506CC3647B152" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="247" pageId="17" pageNumber="246" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3FFFACFCB506CC3647B152" blockId="17.[828,1437,1028,2075]" lastBlockId="18.[151,679,1604,1691]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="247" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3FFFAFFCB506CC378DB0F2" bold="true" box="[828,956,2020,2043]" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name refers to the village of Sauraha at the border of the Chitwan National Park in 
<collectingCountry id="F34D76437A3FFFAFFAD4092C31ACBF12" box="[1373,1437,2052,2075]" name="Nepal" pageId="17" pageNumber="246">Nepal</collectingCountry>
where the 
<typeStatus id="54E188717A3CFFACFE8F076C3552B152" box="[262,355,1604,1627]" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected. Adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
